{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Joan Cadden | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1944 <!-- {{birth date|1944|MM|DD|mf=yes}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1944|MM|DD|mf=yes}} --> | death_place = | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | education = | alma_mater = [[Vassar College]], [[Columbia University]], [[Indiana University]], | occupation = [[Historian]] of science, [[Kenyon College]], [[University of California, Davis]] | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = [[Pfizer Award]] | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | box_width = | website = }}
'''Joan Cadden''' (born 1944) is [[Professor Emerita]] of medieval history and literature in the History Department of the [[University of California, Davis]]. She served as President of the [[History of Science Society]] (HSS) from 2006-2007. She has written extensively on [[gender]] and [[sexuality]] in medieval science and medicine. Her book ''Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Age: Medicine, Science, and Culture'' (1993) received the [[Pfizer Award|Pfizer Prize]] in 1994, from the History of Science Society, as the outstanding book on the history of science.
==Early life and education== Joan Cadden received her B.A. from [[Vassar College]] in 1965,<ref name="Berlin">{{cite web|title=Research Scholars and Guests|url=https://www.mpiwg-berlin.mpg.de/resrep9697/report_96_97.2.html|website=Max Planck Institute for the History of Science in Berlin|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> and her M.A. degree from [[Columbia University]] in 1967, writing her thesis on ''De elementis: Earth, Water, Air, and Fire in the 12th and 13th Centuries.'' She completed her Ph.D. in history and philosophy of science at [[Indiana University]] in 1971. Her Ph.D. thesis was ''The Medieval Philosophy and Biology of Growth: Albertus Magnus, Thomas Aquinas, Albert of Saxony and Marsilius of Inghen on Book I, Chapter V of Aristotle’s ‘De generatione et corruptione,’ with Translated Texts of Albertus and Thomas Aquinas''.<ref name="Bibliography">{{cite journal|first= Chris | last= Africa|title=A Joan Cadden Bibliography|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1856&context=mff|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|pages=127–128|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
==Career== Cadden taught as an assistant professor in the Department of History of Science at [[Harvard University]] from 1971-1976.<ref name="Berlin"/> She was a visiting lecturer in history at the [[University of Colorado, Boulder]] in 1977-1978.<ref name="Isis">{{cite journal|title=Back Matter|journal=Isis|date=1978|volume=69|issue=1|pages=155–158|jstor=230676|doi=10.1086/isis.69.1.230676}}</ref> She taught at [[Kenyon College]] from 1978-1996.<ref name="Berlin"/> She was a Dibner Visiting Historian of Science at [[Purdue University Calumet]] in 1996-1997.<ref name="Smithsonian">{{cite web|title=Dibner Visiting Historian of Science Program Records, 1992-2001|url=http://sirismm.si.edu/EADpdfs/SIA.FA09-218.pdf|website=Smithsonian Institution Archives|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> She joined the [[University of California at Davis]] in 1996 as Professor of History.<ref name="Berlin"/> Cadden served as President of the [[History of Science Society]] (HSS) from 2006-2007.<ref name="HSSPresidents">{{cite web|title=Society Past Presidents|url=http://hssonline.org/about/governance/officers-and-committees/past-presidents/|website=History of Science Society|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> She retired and became Professor Emeritus at UC Davis in 2008.<ref name="Green"/><ref name="UCDavis">{{cite web|title=Joan Cadden|url=http://history.ucdavis.edu/people/fzcadden|website=UC Davis Department of History|accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref>
Her work has been characterized as exploring the "seams of disciplines"—the connections between history of science, gender history, history of sexuality, social history, and intellectual history.<ref name="Puff">{{cite journal|last1=Puff|first1=Helmut|title=Homagium: Joan Cadden's "Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Ages"|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|pages=122–126|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1855&context=mff|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Methodologically, she broke new ground, paying "particular attention to the cultural and social milieux these sources were produced in; to the assumptions and expectations of authors and readers; to questions of form, style, and presentation."<ref name="Lugt"/>
Her book ''Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Age: Medicine, Science, and Culture'' (1993) was groundbreaking in its examination of sex and gender, and has deeply influenced subsequent scholarship.<ref name="Green"/><ref name="Puff"/><ref name="Lugt">{{cite journal|last1=Lugt|first1=Maaike van der|title=Sex Difference in Medieval Theology and Canon Law: A Tribute to Joan Cadden|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|pages=101–121|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1854&context=mff|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Cadden examines the discussions of sexual difference from [[Aristotle]] through the fourteenth century, revealing a wide range of ideas about sexual determination, reproductive roles and sexual pleasure.<ref name="Review">{{cite journal|last1=Park|first1=Katharine|title=Reviewed Work: The Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Ages: Medicine, Science, and Culture by Joan Cadden|journal=Journal of the History of Biology|date=1995|volume=28|issue=3|pages=551–553|jstor=4331368|doi=10.1007/bf01059393}}</ref> She finds multiple models of sexuality in writings throughout the middles ages.<ref name="Hessenbruch">{{cite book |last1=Dreger |first1=Alice D. |last2= Schiebinger |first2=Londa |editor-last= Hessenbruch |editor-first=Arne |title= Reader's guide to the history of science |date=1998 |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |location= London |isbn= 9781884964299 |chapter= Gender and Sex |pages= 287–288 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1wJeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA287 |accessdate= 19 February 2016 }}</ref> This challenged [[Thomas Laqueur]]'s assertion in ''Making Sex: Body and Gender from the Greeks to Freud'' (1990) that male and female were seen as "manifestations of a unified substratum" before the 18th century.<ref name="Park">{{cite journal|last1=Park|first1=Katharine|title=Cadden, Laqueur, and the "One-Sex Body"|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|pages=96–100|url=http://nrs.harvard.edu/urn-3:HUL.InstRepos:4774909|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Cadden addressed medieval discourse in all its "staggering complexity", an "interconnectedness of intellectual interests" that was "far from comforting" in its diversity.<ref name="Puff"/>
She went on to research [[Pietro D'Abano]] and to explore the complexities of medieval natural philosophers' understanding of homosexual desire in her book ''Nothing Natural Is Shameful: Sodomy and Science in Late Medieval Europe'' (2013).<ref name="Nothing">{{cite web|title=Nothing Natural Is Shameful Sodomy and Science in Late Medieval Europe|url=http://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/15155.html|website=University of Pennsylvania Press|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Although she recognizes its limitations, she uses the medieval term "sodomy" to avoid conflation with modern senses of the term "homosexuality". Discussion focuses around Aristotle's ''Problemata IV.26'' and its questioning of male-male sexual desire.<ref name="Kuffner">{{cite journal|last1=Kuffner|first1=Emily|title=Nothing Natural Is Shameful: Sodomy and Science in Late Medieval Europe by Joan Cadden|journal=Comitatus: A Journal of Medieval and Renaissance Studies|date=2014|volume=45|issue=1|pages=215–218|doi=10.1353/cjm.2014.0071|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/274564348_Nothing_Natural_Is_Shameful_Sodomy_and_Science_in_Late_Medieval_Europe_by_Joan_Cadden|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> The book has been described as "a sophisticated reflection on sex and sexuality."<ref name="Nothing"/>
==Awards== Her book ''Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Age: Medicine, Science, and Culture'' (1993) received the 1994 Pfizer Prize for outstanding book on the history of science from the History of Science Society.<ref name="Peek">{{cite journal|last1=Peek|first1=Wendy Chapman|title=Book Reviews|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|date=1995|volume=50|issue=4|pages=563–564|doi=10.1093/jhmas/50.4.563|url=https://jhmas.oxfordjournals.org/content/50/4/563.extract|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> It was the first book on gender studies and the first book in thirty years on medieval studies, to win that award.<ref name="Green">{{cite journal|last1=Green|first1=Monica H.|title=Introduction to Tributes to Joan Cadden|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|pages=63–65|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1848&context=mff|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
Her work was celebrated at two sessions at the 44th annual [[International Congress on Medieval Studies]] in [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]] in 2009 by the [[Society for Medieval Feminist Scholarship]]. The Medieval Foremothers Society honored Joan Cadden in the sessions “Thinking beyond the ‘Woman Writer’ in Reconstructing Women’s Intellectual Worlds,” and “(New) Meanings of Sex Difference in the Middle Ages: Medicine, Science, and Culture (A Roundtable).” These were later published in the ''Medieval Feminist Forum'' (2010).<ref name="MFF">{{cite journal|title=Front matter|journal=Medieval Feminist Forum|date=2010|volume=46|issue=1|url=http://ir.uiowa.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1844&context=mff|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
{{quote|"By listening to multiple voices and embodying synthesis in her own life and career, Joan has allowed us to see a Middle Ages that was always there but was waiting for a skilled interpreter to reveal it." - Monica Green<ref name="Green"/>}}
