{{Orphan|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Marie Hackin |image = Marie Hackin vers 1935.jpg |birth_date = September 7, 1905 |birth_place = [[Rombas]], [[Alsace-Lorraine]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1941|2|24|1905|9|7}} |death_place = near [[Faroe Islands]] |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = French |ethnicity = |field = [[archaeology]] |work_institutions = |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = excavations at [[Bamyan Province|Bamyan]] and [[Bagram]] |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion = }} '''Marie Parmentier''', married name '''Marie Hackin''', (1905-1941) was an archaeologist and Resistance member who worked with her husband [[Joseph Hackin]] who also was an archaeologist, philologist, and Resistance member. Marie Hackin's father was from [[Luxembourg]].<ref>[http://museedelaresistanceenligne.org/media5735-Marie-Hackin-Compagnon-de-la-LibA Musee De La Resistance in Lingue]</ref> She died in 1941 when she was in a sea convoy trying to go from Liverpool into the Atlantic ocean en route to Africa, when the ship was sunk by a German submarine.
