{{Infobox Writer |name = Mary Helen Agnes Allies |image = |imagesize = |caption = |pseudonym = |birth_date = 2 February 1852 |birth_place = London |death_date = {{d-da|27 January 1927|2 February 1852}} |death_place = [[St John's Wood]] |occupation = writer |nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] |period = |genre = |subject = Roman Catholic saints |movement = |debut_works = |influences = [[Thomas William Allies]] |influenced = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Mary Helen Agnes Allies''' (2 February 1852 – 27 January 1927) was a Catholic historian, writer and translator.
==Life== Allies was born on 2 February 1852. She was the eldest daughter of Thomas William and Eliza (born Hall) Allies. Her father had been a fellow at Oxford and he had risen to be the chaplain to the Bishop of London. He had however made a life-changing move to [[Roman Catholicism]] in 1850.<ref name="Gordon-Gorman">{{cite book|author=William James Gordon-Gorman|title=Converts to Rome : a biographical list of the more notable converts to the Catholic Church in the United Kingdom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOvFBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4|publisher=William James Gordon-Gorman|pages=4–|id=GGKEY:A311XT8E38L}}</ref>
Her father was secretary of the [[Catholic Poor School Committee]]. She had five siblings and they lived in St John's Wood in London where it is presumed she was born. The family moved to [[Portman Square]] and Mary boarded at Holy Child College, a Catholic school in [[St Leonards-on-Sea]] operated by the Society of the Holy Child Jesus (later merged into their [[Mayfield School, Mayfield|Mayfield school]]), and subsequently Catholic boarding schools in Paris. Allies gave a lot of respect to her father and in time she would write his biography. She said that she fed "on the marrow of his mind" when she was the only child living at home. Her first work, ''The Life of Pius VII'', was published in 1875. It was well researched, but strongly pro-Catholic. The book looked at [[Pius VII|a supreme pope]] in conflict with the Napoleonic French state. [[Pius VII]]'s conflict included him being arrested. Allies' biography was based on sources in four languages. This, and the shorter version published in 1897,<ref name="Allies1897">{{cite book|author=Mary H. Allies|title=Pius the Seventh (1800-1823), by Mary H. Allies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gephQwAACAAJ|year=1897|publisher=Burns}}</ref> is still (2004) the only available biography of Pius VII in English and is therefore a [[standard work]].<ref name=mary/>
Her next work was considered too pious and uncritical of her subjects. She wrote about the Dominican friar Saint [[Vincent Ferrer|Vincent Ferrier]], Saint [[Bernardino of Siena]] and the "Soldier Saint" [[John of Capistrano]]. Her next work was taken from the works Saint Augustine which was published in 1886<ref name=mary/> and this was followed up by his letters.<ref name="Augustin1890">{{cite book|author=saint Augustin|title=Letters: Of Saint-Augustine, Selected and Translated by Mary H. Allies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBlFQwAACAAJ|year=1890|publisher=Burns and Oates}}</ref> In the interim she published a book about another Catholic saint, [[John Chrysostom]], in 1889. A different title was ''The History of the Church of England'' which she published between 1892 and 1897. This was a partisan view of the Anglican church before 1603.<ref name=mary/>
She translated an extract of [[John of Damascus]]'s ''De fide Orthoxa'' in 1898. When her mother died in 1902 and her father the following year she occupied herself writing a biography of her father,<ref name=bio>APA citation. Allies, M.H. (1907). Thomas William Allies. In The Catholic Encyclopedia. New York: Robert Appleton Company. Retrieved 11 December 2015 from New Advent:
http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/01323b.htm</ref> writing journal articles and caring for her brother's children. She died at her home in St John's Wood in 1927.<ref name=mary>Rosemary Mitchell, ‘Allies, Mary Helen Agnes (1852–1927)’, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/55544, accessed 11 Dec 2015]</ref>
