{{Infobox museum | name = Plumas County Museum
| image = | caption =
| map_type = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|39.9356|-120.9477|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}} | established = 1971 | dissolved = | location = [[Quincy, California]] | type = [[History museum]] | collection = | visitors = | director = Scott Lawson | president = | curator = | publictransit = | network = | website = {{URL|https://plumasmuseum.org/}} }}
The '''Plumas County Museum''' is a 501(c)3 organization and historical museum located in [[Quincy, California]]. Exhibits focus on [[Plumas County, California|Plumas County]], including the [[Maidu]] people, the [[California Gold Rush]], the logging industry,<ref>[http://www.plumasnews.com/from-the-forests-to-the-fairgrounds/] ''From the forests to the fairgrounds''</ref> and the local community.
In addition to artifacts on display, the museum houses an archive of over 5,000 photographs, as well as documents, and a 1,000-item map collection.
The museum is owned and managed by an association, which also owns and maintains the 1878 [[Variel Home]] as well as the 1859 [[Goodwin Law Office]], the oldest continually used law office in the state of California.<ref>[https://www.plumasmuseum.org/ "Plumas County Museum"] ''Plumas County Museum'' Retrieved 14 Jun 2017.</ref>
==History== The museum was endowed by the estate of Stella Fay Miller of [[Quincy, California]].
