'''Vaso Čubrilović''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|Васо Чубриловић}}; 14 January 1897&nbsp;– 11 June 1990) was a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]] scholar and Yugoslav politician. As a teenager, he joined the South Slav student movement known as [[Young Bosnia]] and was involved in the conspiracy to [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand|assassinate]] [[Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria]] on 28 June 1914. His brother, [[Veljko Čubrilović|Veljko]], was also involved in the plot. Čubrilović was convicted of treason by the Austro-Hungarian authorities and given a sixteen-year sentence; his brother was sentenced to death and executed. Čubrilović was released from prison at war's end and studied history at the universities of [[University of Zagreb|Zagreb]] and [[University of Belgrade|Belgrade]]. In 1937, he delivered a lecture to the Serbian Cultural Club in which he advocated [[The Expulsion of the Albanians]] from Yugoslavia. Two years later, he became a history professor at the [[University of Belgrade]]. Following the [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] in April 1941, Čubrilović was arrested by the Germans and sent to the [[Banjica concentration camp]], where he remained imprisoned for much of the war.

As World War II drew to a close, Čubrilović urged the Yugoslav authorities to expel ethnic minorities (particularly Germans and Hungarians) from the country. At war's end, he became a government minister. In his position as Minister of Agriculture, he pushed for the implementation of agricultural reforms. In his later years, he distanced himself from the Pan Slav, and later nationalist, ideologies of his youth and expressed regret over Franz Ferdinand's assassination. At the time of his death, he was the last surviving participant in the conspiracy to kill the Archduke.

==Early life==
Vaso Čubrilović was born in [[Gradiška, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosanska Gradiška]] on 14 January 1897.{{sfn|Elsie|2010|p=69}} His was a well known family from the region of [[Bosanska Krajina]]. He was a relative of [[Vaso Vidović]], a leader of the 1875–77 [[Herzegovina Uprising (1875–77)|Herzegovina Uprising]] who attended the [[Congress of Berlin]].{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=304}} Čubrilović finished primary school in his hometown.{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=3}} He went on to attend the Tuzla High School but was expelled for refusing to stand during the Austro-Hungarian national anthem. He subsequently enrolled in the sixth class of the Sarajevo High School.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=304}}

==Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand and World War I==
[[File:Vaso Čubrilović.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Čubrilović in Austro-Hungarian police custody, October 1914.]]
Čubrilović had been a member of [[Young Bosnia]] prior to the outbreak of [[World War I]].{{sfn|Elsie|2010|p=69}} He and his older brother were involved in the conspiracy to [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|assassinate]] of Archduke [[Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|Franz Ferdinand]] on 28 June 1914. The younger Čubrilović was the youngest of the conspirators.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=314}} He was arrested by the Austro-Hungarian authorities in [[Bosanska Dubica]] on 3 July.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|pp=332–333}} The main conspirators were tried in a military prison in Sarajevo. The state attorney charged twenty-two of the accused with high treason and first-degree murder and three with complicity to commit murder. The trial began on 12 October and lasted until 23 October. Čubrilović was only 17 years and six months old at the time.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=336}} The Čubrilović brothers, [[Ivo Kranjčević]] and [[Neđo Kerović]] were defended by the lawyer Rudolf Cistler.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=336}} At the trial, Čubrilović stated that the mistreatment of South Slavs by the Habsburgs motived him to take part in the plot.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=338}} "I can state that the monarchy is ruled by the Germans and the Magyars while the Slavs are oppressed," he said.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=338}} Asked if he identified as a Serb or a Croat, Čubrilović declared himself a Serbo-Croat. "It means I don't consider myself solely a Serb," he explained, "but that I must work for Croatia as well as for Serbia."{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=90}} Though the trial ended on 23 October, sentencing did not occur until five days later. Čubrilović was convicted of treason and given a sixteen-year sentence.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=346}} He had initially been sentenced to ten years' imprisonment. When asked his religious beliefs, he identified as an [[Atheism|atheist]], prompting the judges to add another three years.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=212}} A further three were added after he refused to express remorse for the Archduke's death and blamed Austria-Hungary for starting the war.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=341}} His brother Veljko was sentenced to death and hanged.{{sfn|Carmichael|2015|p=55}}

Čubrilović was initially sent to serve out his sentence in [[Zenica]].{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=351}} On 2 March, he and some of his co-conspirators were relocated to the Möllersdorf military prison, near [[Vienna]].{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=353}} They were re-tried in [[Travnik]] on 14 June 1915, and had several years added to their sentences.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=347}} Čubrilović was subsequently moved back to Möllersdorf. On 13 September 1917, the authorities decided to move almost all the surviving conspirators to Zenica prison. He remained imprisoned in Zenica until the end of the war.{{sfn|Dedijer|1966|p=361}}

==Interwar period==
Čubrilović completed his high school education in Sarajevo in 1919. First, he enrolled at the [[University of Zagreb]] to study history, but later transferred to the [[University of Belgrade]], where he received a [[Bachelor's degree]] in history in 1922. In 1929, he obtained his [[Ph.D]] at the University of Belgrade with a thesis titled "The Bosnian Uprising 1875–1878". In the meantime, he had worked as a history teacher at high schools in [[Sremska Mitrovica]], Sarajevo and Belgrade. The historian [[Vladimir Ćorović]] subsequently selected Čubrilović as his personal assistant. In 1934, Čubrilović became a [[docent]] at the university. From 1921 to 1939, he was an active member of the [[Agrarian Party (Yugoslavia)|Agrarian Party]].{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=3}}

In 1937, Čubrilović delivered a lecture to the [[Serbian Cultural Club]] in which he outlined possible methods the Yugoslav government could use to coerce [[Albanians]] into leaving Kosovo. Čubrilović argued that the only way to "deal" with the Albanians was to use the "brute force of an organized state". "If we do not settle accounts with them," he opined, "in 20–30 years we shall have to cope with a terrible irredentism."{{sfn|Judah|2000|p=149}} He was highly critical of government attempts to [[Colonisation of Kosovo|colonize]] parts of Kosovo as he felt they were ineffective.{{sfn|Judah|2002|p=23}}{{efn|Between 1918 and 1945, about 45,000 Albanians left Kosovo, mostly to Turkey. They were replaced by 60,000 Serb settlers in the [[interwar period]].{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=100}} Tens of thousands of these settlers were expelled by the Albanians during [[World War II]] and were not allowed to return to Kosovo by Tito's post-war government.{{sfn|Judah|2000|p=150}}}} Čubrilović also criticized the government for not having seized the opportunity presented by a 1918–21 revolt among Kosovo Albanians to force them out of the region. He stated that the benefits of the forced expulsion of Albanians outweighed any risk since "a threat to Yugoslav security would be removed". He reasoned: "At a time when Germany can expel tens of thousands of Jews and Russia can shift millions of people from one part of the continent to another, the shifting of a few Albanians will not lead to the outbreak of a world war."{{sfn|Judah|2002|p=23}} The content of the lecture was preserved in writing, came into the possession of Yugoslavia's military intelligence service and was preserved at the Military Archive in Belgrade.{{sfn|Bjelajac|2007|p=223}} It was not made public until 1988.{{sfn|Anžulović|1999|loc=p. 199, note 66}} In the ensuing decades, Albanian historians have referred to it as evidence of a plot to evict Kosovo's Albanian population, usually claiming it was written at the request of the Yugoslav General Staff. However, there is no evidence to this effect.{{sfn|Bjelajac|2007|p=223}} Professor [[Sabrina P. Ramet]] doubts the lecture had much influence on the Yugoslav authorities, who were already long committed to seeing Kosovo Albanians leave the province and emigrate to Turkey.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=100}}

==World War II and later life==
In 1939, Čubrilović became a professor at the University of Belgrade.{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=3}} In April 1941, the [[Axis powers]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded Yugoslavia]], and Čubrilović was arrested by the [[Gestapo]] in the coastal town of [[Risan]].{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=4}} From there, he was transferred to Belgrade and imprisoned at the [[Banjica concentration camp]], where he remained for much of the war.{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=4}}{{sfn|Nešović|1981|p=728}} Once German forces had been forced out of Serbia, Čubrilović became an advisor to Yugoslavia's new [[Communism|communist]] leader, [[Josip Broz Tito]].{{sfn|Carmichael|2015|p=63}} The anti-Serb pogroms of World War II, particularly those orchestrated by the Albanians, again directed Čubrilović's attention to the status of Yugoslavia's national minorities.{{sfn|Judah|2000|p=150}} On 17 November 1944, in Belgrade, Čubrilović presented a memorandum titled "The Minority Problem in the New Yugoslavia" ({{lang-sh-Latn|Manjinski problem u novoj Jugoslaviji}}) to the communist authorities.{{sfn|Elsie|2010|p=69}} In it, he advised Tito's government to expel all of Yugoslavia's Germans, Hungarians, Italians, Romanians and Albanians. Indeed, virtually all ethnic Germans living in the country were forced out, as were many Hungarians and Romanians. "The minority problem," Čubrilović wrote, "if we don't solve it now, will never be solved."{{sfn|Judah|2002|pp=31–32}} At the time, such suggestions did not come across as particularly radical given that they coincided with the [[Flight and expulsion of Germans (1944–50)|mass expulsion of Germans]] from other parts of Central and Eastern Europe.{{sfn|Judah|2000|p=150}}

In early 1945, Čubrilović was appointed Minister of Agriculture in Tito's government.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=311}} In August of that year, he pushed for the implementation of the Law on State Agricultural Farms, which emphasized the need to undertake economic measures that would rebuild and strengthen Yugoslavia's agricultural sector.{{sfn|Bokovoy|1998|pp=45, 61}} Čubrilović was later appointed Minister of Forestry.<ref name="UBL">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Banja Luka]]|title=Academician Prof. Dr. Vaso Čubrilović|url=http://www.unibl.rs/en/page/Academician-Prof-Dr-Vaso-Subrilovic/5|access-date=2015-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122011018/http://www.unibl.rs/en/page/Academician-Prof-Dr-Vaso-Subrilovic/5|archive-date=2015-11-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> In 1959, he became a correspondent of the [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] (SANU), and in 1961, he was granted full membership. Čubrilović was also a correspondent of the [[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts|Yugoslav]] and [[Academy of Sciences and Arts of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian]] academies of sciences and arts, and a regular member of the [[Montenegrin Academy of Sciences and Arts]]. In 1976, he became an honorary member of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Soviet Academy of Sciences]].{{sfn|Matica Srpska|1997|p=4}} In his later years, Čubrilović distanced himself from the Pan Slav, and later nationalist, ideologies of his youth.{{sfn|Carmichael|2015|p=63}} Referring to Franz Ferdinand's assassination, he said: "We destroyed a beautiful world that was lost forever due to the war that followed."{{sfn|Sugar|1999|p=70}} In 1986, he expressed public disapproval of the [[Memorandum of the Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts|SANU memorandum]], which argued that Yugoslavia's Serbs were being discriminated against and called for a fundamental reorganization of the state.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2002|loc=p. 191, note 4}} In 1987, the [[Presidium of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav Presidency]] awarded Čubrilović the [[Order of the Yugoslav Star]].{{sfn|Gaber|Kuzmanić|1989|p=51}} He died in Belgrade on 11 June 1990, aged 93.{{sfn|Elsie|2010|p=69}} At the time of his death, he was the last surviving participant in the conspiracy to kill Franz Ferdinand.{{sfn|Sugar|1999|p=70}}

