{{Infobox person | name = Zvi Elpeleg | image = צבי אלפלג.jpg | alt = | caption = Zvi Elpeleg at the wedding of his young brother, Yerach | birth_name = | birth_date = 1926 <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. --> | birth_place = Baranow, [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2015|6|27|1926|df=y}} | death_place = | nationality = [[Israel]]i | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | spouse = [[Michal Snunit]] }}
'''Zvi Elpeleg''' (1926 – 27 June 2015) was an academic, author, and a senior researcher at the [[Dayan Institute]] at [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref name=Teitelbaum/> Born in Poland, Elpeleg served as a [[colonel]] in the [[Israeli army]]<ref name=Bitterlemons/> and later received an ambassadorial appointment.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Herz |editor1-first=Dietmar |editor2-last=Jetzlsperger |editor2-first=Christian |editor3-last=Ahlborn |editor3-first=Kai |year=2003 |title=Der israelisch-palästinensische Konflikt: Hintergründe, Dimensionen und Perspektiven |location=Stuttgart |publisher=Franz Steiner Verlag |isbn=3-515-08259-X |page=227 }}</ref>
Elpeleg was born in 1926 in Baranow, [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] to his parents Rivka (née Zayfntreger) and Yosef Elphlang. His father was a carpenter and his mother a house wife. Elpeleg was the second of four siblings: Hadasa (1924), David (1928) and Yerachmiel (1929). In 1934 the family came to Israel and settled in the Makabi-Tzrifim neighbourhood in Jaffa. Following David Ben-Gurion instruction that officers should change their family name to a Hebrew one, Elpeleg changed his name from Elphlang to Elpeleg. In the mid-1950s Elpeleg was the military governor of [[Triangle (Israel)|the Triangle]] and from 1956 to 1957 the military governor of [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]].<ref name=Bitterlemons>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mediamonitors.net/zvielpeleg1.html |title=Respect their philosophy of survival (end note bio) |first=Zvi |last=Elpeleg |publisher=Bitterlemons.org / Media monitors |year=2002}}</ref><ref name=Fisk>{{Cite web |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20010601/ai_n14385241 |title=Obituary: Faisal Husseini |first=Robert |last=Fisk |authorlink=Robert Fisk |publisher=The Independent (London) |date=2001-06-01}}</ref> He became Israel's first military governor of the [[West Bank]] in 1967.<ref name=Teitelbaum>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hadassah.org/news/content/per_hadassah/archive/2000/Jan/one.htm |title=One on One: Portrait of Michal Snunit |first=Sheldon |last=Teitelbaum |publisher=Hasassah Magazine |date=January 2000 |access-date=2008-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906002437/http://www.hadassah.org/news/content/per_hadassah/archive/2000/Jan/one.htm |archive-date=2004-09-06 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> He would repeat the role during the Israeli occupation of the [[RAF Fayid|Fayid region]] in Egypt in 1973, and again in [[South Lebanon conflict (1982–2000)#Occupation period 1982–1985 – the emergence of Hizbullah|occupied South Lebanon]] in 1982.<ref name=Bitterlemons/>
He served as [[Israel]]'s [[ambassador]] to [[Turkey]] from 1995 to 1997.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Turkey: Facing a New Millennium : Coping With Intertwined Conflicts |first=Amikam |last=Nachmani |pages=209 |year=2003 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=0-7190-6370-1}}</ref>
He entered academia as an [[Arabist]] and, since 1972, he has been attached, as senior researcher, to the Dayan Institute.<ref name=Bitterlemons/> He has authored a biography of [[Haj Amin al-Husseini]],<ref>Zvi Elpeleg, ''The Grand Mufti: Haj Amin Al-Hussaini, Founder of the Palestinian National Movement'', Frank Cass Publishers, 1991. {{ISBN|0-7146-4100-6}}.</ref> which is considered one of the standard works on the man.
Zvi Elpeleg served as chairman of the Turkey-Israel Friendship Association and was appointed Turkey's honorary consul to Tel Aviv by the former Turkish president [[Süleyman Demirel]]<ref name=Honorary>{{Cite web |url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/yazarDetay.do?haberno=30426 |title=Today's Zaman |publisher=Today's Zaman |year=2006 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in gratitude for the role he played in overseeing Israeli IDF Aid for Turkish Earthquake Victims in August 1999.<ref name=Aid>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.il/MFA/MFAArchive/1990_1999/1999/8/Israeli%20Aid%20for%20Turkish%20Earthquake%20Victims |title=Israeli IDF Aid for Turkish Earthquake Victims |publisher=Israeli Foreign Ministry |year=1999}}</ref>
He was married to the poet [[Michal Snunit]]. Elpeleg died on 27 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Memory of Dr. Zvi Elpeleg|url=http://www.dayan.org/memory-dr-zvi-elpeleg|publisher=Tel Aviv University|accessdate=29 June 2015 |archivedate=August 13, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813134722/http://dayan.org/memory-dr-zvi-elpeleg }}</ref>
